            "content": "Not every inspection identifying problems requires complete roof replacement—understanding when repairs adequately protect your home versus when replacement makes financial sense prevents both premature replacement and delayed action causing expensive damage. Repair Makes Sense When: Remaining roof life exceeds 5-7 years based on material condition and age, identified problems are localized to specific areas rather than system-wide, total repair costs are under 30% of replacement cost, roof structure and decking remain sound, and no major installation deficiencies exist affecting overall performance. Replacement Makes Sense When: Remaining serviceable life is under 3-5 years making repair investment temporary, identified problems are widespread affecting majority of roof area, total repair costs exceed 40-50% of replacement cost, underlying waterproofing (underlayment) has failed requiring complete roof removal, structural problems exist requiring deck replacement or major framing repairs, multiple previous repairs suggest systemic problems rather than isolated issues, or insurance will cover major portion of replacement after recent storm damage. Consider Your Timeline: If you plan selling within 2-3 years, targeted repairs may provide adequate protection without investment in full replacement you won't benefit from. If you plan remaining in home 10+ years, replacement providing 20-30 years additional life may offer better long-term value than repairs buying only 3-5 years."
